Product Description

What's new on K4v2?

  • Bluetooth 5.1.
  • Inclined bottom frame.
  • Relocated the Del key.
  • Changed keycap color scheme.
  • Added dedicated caps lock indicator light.
PACKAGE CONTENT:

  • 1 x Keychron K4 Mechanical Keyboard
  • 1 x Windows Keycaps
  • 1 x USB-A to USB Type-C Cable
  • 1 x Keycap Puller
  • 1 x User Manual

Compact Bluetooth Mechanical Keyboard

A 96% layout (100-key) White LED backlight wireless mechanical keyboard （without hot-swappable）with a number pad in a compact design that’s built for productivity and a tactile typing experience.

With a unique Mac layout provides all necessary Mac function keys, while compatible with Windows. It connects with up to 3 devices with the latest Broadcom Bluetooth 5.1 chipset proved from time to time.

Gateron G Pro mechanical Brown Switch

Durable Gateron G Pro mechanical switch with a 50 million keystroke lifespan to provide an unrivaled tactile responsiveness on the Brown switches.

Read more

Bluetooth Mechanical Keyboard

A 96% layout (100-key) wireless mechanical keyboard included number pad and relocated Del key that offers convenient access to all the essential keys for Mac and Windows in a small footprint. (*Num Lock works with Windows OS only.)

Wireless and Wired Dual Modes

Connects with up to 3 devices via Bluetooth and switch among them easily. With high reliable and broad compatibility Broadcom Bluetooth 5.1 chipset, the K4 is best to fit home, office and light gaming use while connecting with your smartphone, laptop and iPad. It also has wired mode with USB Type-C connection.

Suitable for All Devices

With a unique Mac layout and Windows compatibility, the K4 is offering convenient accessibility to all the essential multimedia and function keys. Just plug and use, no driver is needed. Extra keycaps for both Windows and Mac operating systems are included.

Read more

4000mAh Big Battery

The K4 can last up to 240 hours (with backlit disabled) with a 4000 mAh big battery, which is one of the biggest in mechanical keyboards. N-key rollover (NKRO) on wired mode or 6KRO on wireless mode.

One More Thing

Inclined bottom frame makes the K4 version 2 more comfortable to crank out emails or write a novel. Added dedicated caps lock indicator light and relocated the Del key base as customer feedback.

Community Driven Design

Covered by major tech media which thanks to our community that contributed to make a perfect design.

How customer reviews and ratings work

Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we don’t use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzed reviews to verify trustworthiness.

3.0 out of 5 stars Way to high off desk. Feels cheap.
Reviewed in the United States on January 10, 2020
K4 with mechanic gaetron blue switches with the white LED on plastic baseI really wanted to love this keyboard. The reviews of the K2 are great and I love my current mechanical keyboard from Havit with the blue switches. I ordered this K4 with the gaetron blue switches with the plastic she'll expecting a similar experience. I really want a Bluetooth mechanical keyboard and this key layout and battery size was very appealing.Pros:The Bluetooth worked flawlesslyMultimedia keys worked right out of the boxIt looks coolThey key layout in this compact does GN is perfect. I absolutely love the layout and how small lengthwise it makes the keyboard.Cons:It is HIGH off the desk. Needlessly high. I uploaded pictures of it next to my Havit mechanical keyboard with the same switches. The tip of my highest switch doesn't even reach the base of the lowest key on this keyboard. You will really need a wrist rest as there is just no way to rest your wrist on the desk in from of it.The keys are wobbly. If one brushes their hands across the keys they all move and make noise. My Havit doesn’t do this at all. All the keys are pretty steady and noiseThe hollow piece of plastic under this makes the typing so loud. Sure the keys have the clickiness and I like that. These keys bottom out on the plastic base and it’s just loud. Hammering loud. It feels cheap to me. I suppose you may say “well I’ll get the aluminum one”. Go watch a few YouTube videos about someone dissembling this K4. The base is all plastic, even where the switches are mounted. Aluminum simply covers the plastic base. The base is plastic. Go check it out.I really wish they would compress this plastic base. It’s just a big hollow empty space with a battery in it. It seems they could move the battery and the Bluetooth switch to the back to bring the keyboard down quite a bit.I had to send it back. The search for a blue took mechanical keyboard continues.

Meghan Bell
5.0 out of 5 stars Great feel and well priced
Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on September 14, 2022
Color: Gateron G Pro Brown SwitchVerified Purchase
I wanted a mechanical keyboard for work that didn't light up like a rave or cost a couple of hundred bucks.

I got the brown switches as I am mostly using it for typing in excel/word and in my experience red gives too many errors and blues drive everyone else around me nuts from the clacking. The key presses feel good and give a solid click without going too overboard. My typing is significantly faster then on my previous membrane board and I don't feel like I'm smooshing keys into a piece of rubber anymore.

The matte finish on the board looks great and the color scheme with the light and dark grey keys and orange accents make it feel almost like a custom keyset. It comes with a key remover and mac/windows specific keys which is also a nice touch.

The backlighting is subtle and looks professional so it works well in an office setting. Because the keys are backlit you can utilize it in low light settings and still read the keys.

I use Excel quite a bit so having the Numpad was really important to me. This utilizes a condensed keypad which gives you all the utility without sacrificing too much desk space. The arrow keys being shifted over takes some getting used to if you are flying on a sheet but overall its worth it for having a smaller overall keyboard.

Bluetooth worked right out of the box. I have been running it wired lately so I don't ever have to worry about battery life.

I've only had it a couple of weeks so I can't attest to its overall durability. Other similarly priced boards have lasted under a year for me so if it can beat that Ill be a happy camper.

Great entry board if you are just getting your feet wet with mechanical boards for gaming or if you are just trying to get something for work that doesn't break the bank or look rediculous in your office. Any gamer in the office will be jealous when they hear you click-clacking away. ( I've had a few notice already)

VINE VOICE
4.0 out of 5 stars Not enough features for the price. Some build quality issues
Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on September 23, 2022
Color: Gateron G Pro Blue SwitchVerified Purchase
First of all, the board feels very solid and the keys have minimum side to side or twisting motion. Bluetooth works great. I expect no less from a keyboard at this price range.

Where it has issues: The two switches on the side for power and Mac/Windows mode are extremely cheap. For such a solid board, these two dinky switches feel like an afterthought. At some point I had dropped the keyboard while I was swapping keys (a relatively light fall from maybe a couple feet), and the power switch popped out of alignment. I'm happy that it's very easy to take the board apart to realign the switch, but now I see how those switches are very cheap and thin. I expect they will pop out or even break after a few months of daily use if you have a habit of turning it off to save battery life.

My second issue is with the back-lighting. I have the white LED version, and I'm disappointed with the built-in presets and brightness levels. The backlight key is on the top right of the keyboard, so when I'm sitting with this keyboard on my lap, I frequently bump that key. Then I have to press it a dozen times to get it back to a solid backlight.
Also, the backlight brightness doesn't have enough levels, and I find the lowest still pretty bright in a dark room. Unfortunately, they offer no software to tweak the lighting presets. Programming software should be included at this price level, but instead they just recommend some 3rd party key mapping apps.

Lastly, I would have liked the Print Screen and Insert keys as a Fn+ key. Especially the Insert key, because it's commonly used in games like Flight sims.

If you buy this, I just want to caution against using the power switch frequently, because it will likely break. Either leave it on 24/7 and hope the sleep mode is good, or use it with a USB cable all the time. Or just be very gentle with it.

4.0 out of 5 stars Fantastic keyboard, but not suitable for writing code.
Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on May 9, 2022
Color: Gateron G Pro Brown SwitchVerified Purchase
I liked this keyboard but ultimately ended up returning it.

I'm a fast typer, 110+ WPM, and I do a lot of front and backend software development. I was really locked into my old fullsize mechanical keyboard (Logitech G610), and I could fly around that thing like nobody's business. On this keyboard, I found myself making navigational mistakes which were detrimental to my workflow.

For example, I use the arrow keys in combination with shift, ctrl, home and end, to select entire words or lines of text quickly, or jump to the top/bottom of documents. With the arrow keys on the 96% Keychron being physically indistinguishable from the keys next to it, I had to look down at the keys to see where they were. After I thought I got the feeling of it, I'd try without looking, and would often hit an incorrect arrow key. Additionally, the strange placement of the home, end, and delete keys required similar effort to find and use properly.

I didn't realize how big of a deal this would be for me, and I might be a little bit dramatic, but mis-pressing one of these keys was jarring to my productivity. I navigate through code with the arrow and home/end/shift/ctrl keys so frequently that it is second nature, as if they are one with my thoughts, just like typing normally. You know how it is, you don't have to think about typing, you just do it. Imagine typing words and you mistakenly hit the wrong letter frequently. It wasn't until after giving the 96% layout a try that I realized how important a full size layout was to me.

So, what I did like about the keyboard was:
* The ability to use a cable (not just for charging, but for actual keyboard-functionality), AND that the cable is USB-C to USB-A.
* The brown switches are quite nice. They're quiet yet they give enough feedback that promotes confidence.
* The color scheme of the keyboard. Plus, even on the white-only backlit keyboard, the number lock and caps lock light up red when enabled.

I am missing the multimedia controls from the Logitech G610. The volume wheel and dedicated play/pause/next/mute buttons really come in handy when working from home and getting a phone call. The Keychron provides the same functionality, but they're only activated with the Fn key. You can change the board so that the functions are accessible without needing the Fn key, but then you have to use the Fn key to access the normal F keys. And for web development or working in Excel, that's a hassle.

The Win/Mac LED indicators on the top right are silly for something that changes so infrequently (for me, at least). If you work on both a Mac and Windows, you might find it useful to know, but there is a toggle switch on the side of the frame to choose which OS you want the keyboard to map to. I just feel like they could have put some multimedia controls in that section.

I ended up buying the full size Keychron K10 RGB. It has the same gripes with the Fn key and multimedia controls, but I really did need the fullsize layout.

T F
3.0 out of 5 stars Nice and compact, but design compromises may make it unsuitable for coding
Reviewed in Canada 🇨🇦 on September 29, 2020
Color: Gateron G Pro Brown SwitchVerified Purchase
I'm a software developer, and was looking for a compact mechanical keyboard for coding and general documentation. I also needed to switch between multiple machines., and I needed to use the number pad and function keys frequently. The Keychron K4 seemed to tick all the boxes I needed. Overall, it's painfully close, but there were far too many irritations that stop me from wholeheartedly recommending the keyboard for programmers. It may be fine for other users, though.

Pros:
- Good construction, even with the basic plastic version. No flex in the chassis.

- Compact dimensions, even with a number pad

- Easy Bluetooth connectivity to multiple machines

- Great value. Lots of features for the money.

- Probably the only compact Bluetooth mechanical keyboard with a numeric keypad on the market.

Cons:
- Problematic keyboard layout: I can see how Keychron tried to squeeze arrow keys onto the keyboard by tucking them underneath the Enter key. This causes a significant design compromise by reducing right-shift key to make space for the up-arrow. If you're a programmer, this requires you to contort your right hand to type some common special characters (brackets, asterisk, underscore, plus sign, braces, colon, etc). If you're coding in a C-like language, this may be a big issue. They layout may be uncomfortable for some, and would be a dealbreaker for those with repetitive stress injuries.

- You can't visually determine the capslock status unless you apply a firmware update, and use a clumsy toggle

- You can't visually determine the number lock status, and there is NO firmware update to resolve this. This isn't a big deal for those who rarely use the number pad, but it's irritating to me. To top of this, numlock only works with a Bluetooth connection.

- There's no Print Screen button, unless you use the clumsy firmware solution. It's not a problem on Windows 10 (just use the Windows+Shift-S chord), but it may be an issue with other operating systems. I would happily move the lighting button to the side of the unit, and put a print screen button in its place.

Other issues, that may/may not be problems:
- The Gateron Brown switches are significantly softer then the Cherry MX Browns or the Kailh browns. I got used to it, but others may find them too mushy.

- The switches on the side of the unit to control MacOS/Windows, and Wired/off/Bluetooth are very small, and the labeling is barely legible. It may be annoying to some users.

- If you use Function keys, there is NO physical spacing between the function key row and the numbers. Keychron's older K1 has this spacing, and I can see why the spacing was eliminated for maximum compactness, but I'd gladly add a little bit of depth to get the spacing.

- If you use the Number Pad, there is NO physical spacing between the main keyboard and the number pad. This isn't necessarily a huge deal, but there's little visual contrast between the number pad and the main keyboard besides the slight colour keycap difference. It's hard to discern in low light. I would happily add 5mm of width to the keyboard to add a gap.

- The LED indicator lights are on the far-side of the unit. The tall keys hide the lights, which means you need to lean over to see the status. Perhaps these should be on the corner or on the left/right side?

Overall, the Keychron K4 has so much potential, but it needs some refinement as a programming keyboard. Some issues may be fixed by firmware (e.g. Caps lock and num lock toggle), but other issues cannot (e.g. keyboard layout issues, like the small right-shift key, and oddly placed indicator lights). If you're not a coder, this keyboard may be ideal. But for me, it's not.

[Additional Comment: After 3 weeks of using the keyboard, I'm returning it. The small size of the right-shift key, and the lack of spacing for the numpad and function key rows were driving me nuts. I couldn't get used to the keyboard layout. I replaced the keyboard with a wired TKL layout keyboard]
